  m_Name: ManualPage1
  m_EditorClassIdentifier: 
  pageIndex: 0
  pageTitle: Welcome To RouterCo
  leftPageBody: 'POST Requests:

    A POST request is used to send data from the
    client to the server, typically in the request body (often JSON or form data),
    to create or modify resources. To determine if a POST request is safe, the user
    should focus on the body fields and any user-supplied values, looking for unusual
    patterns such as embedded commands (;, &&), script tags, or unexpected data types.
    Safe POST requests usually contain clean, well-formed data that matches the expected
    input (e.g., a normal IP address or username), while unsafe ones often include
    extra characters or commands that suggest injection attempts or misuse of the
    server.


    Safe Example:

    POST /api/register HTTP/1.1\nHost: example.com\nContent-Type:
    application/json\n{\n  \"username\": \"mjohnson\",\n  \"email\": \"mjohnson@example.com\",\n 
    \"password\": \"S3cur3P@ssw0rd!\"\n}'
  rightPageBody: 'GET requests

    A GET request is used to retrieve data from the
    server, with parameters typically included in the URL query string. To evaluate
    safety, the user should examine the query parameters, since these are often user-controlled,
    and check for suspicious additions like SQL keywords (UNION, SELECT), encoded
    characters (%60, %3B), or attempts to manipulate file paths (../). Safe GET requests
    generally have simple, expected parameter values, while unsafe ones include injected
    code or malformed inputs designed to exploit how the server processes those parameters.


    Safe
    Example:

    GET /api/products?category=books&sort=rating&order=desc&page=1
    HTTP/1.1\nHost: example.com\nAccept: application/json\nAuthorization: Bearer
    eyJhbGciOiJIUzI1NiJ9.exampletoken123'
  difficultyTag: 
  unlockThreshold: 0
